10.1 What Are Semantic Elements?

Semantic HTML clearly describes the meaning of the content.

These elements help browsers, developers, and assistive tech (like screen readers).

Examples: <article>, <section>, <header>, <footer>, <aside>, <nav>

10.2 Benefits of Semantic HTML

Improved SEO (Search engines understand page structure better)

Better Accessibility (screen readers and tools interpret your page correctly)

Code Readability (easy to understand structure)

10.3 Common Semantic Elements

<header>

Represents introductory content or navigation links.

<header>
  <h1>Site Title</h1>
  <nav>...</nav>
</header>

<nav>

Used for primary navigation menus.

<nav>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="/home">Home</a></li>
    <li><a href="/about">About</a></li>
  </ul>
</nav>

<main>

The central content of the document. One per page.

<main>
  <article>...</article>
</main>

<article>

Independent content like blog posts, comments, news articles.

<article>
  <h2>Blog Title</h2>
  <p>Blog content...</p>
</article>

<section>

A thematic grouping of content.

<section>
  <h2>Features</h2>
  <ul>...</ul>
</section>

<aside>

Side content such as ads, sidebars, or pull quotes.

<aside>
  <h3>Advertisement</h3>
  <p>Buy our product!</p>
</aside>

<footer>

Footer of the section or document.

<footer>
  <p>&copy; 2025 My Website</p>
</footer>

10.4 Non-Semantic vs Semantic Elements

Non-Semantic

Semantic

<div>

<section>

<span>

<article>

<b>

<strong>

<i>

<em>

10.5 Semantic Inline Tags

<strong>: Strong importance

<em>: Emphasis

<abbr>: Abbreviations

<cite>: Citation

<mark>: Highlighted text

<code>: Inline code

Example:

<p>Use the <code>&lt;header&gt;</code> tag to define introductory content.</p>

10.6 Accessibility Tips

Use semantic elements for screen readers.

Add aria-* attributes only when semantic HTML doesn't convey the info.

Headings (<h1> to <h6>) must be used in order.
